    {# ===================================================================== #}
    <section class="ff-guide-block">
      <div class="ff-guide-block-head">
        <span class="ff-guide-num">14</span>
        <h2>Longform text with drop-cap</h2>
        <p class="ff-guide-block-note">For written pages and posts. Serif drop-cap, generous measure and leading.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ff-guide-variant">
        <p class="ff-guide-var-label">Selected direction: classic serif drop-cap</p>
        <p class="ff-guide-var-desc">A navy serif drop-cap opens the first paragraph, with a readable measure and open leading. Subheads set in the display serif.</p>
        <div class="ff-longform">
          <p>Most people who come in for anxiety have already tried very hard to think their way out of it. They have read the books, rehearsed the conversations, and planned for outcomes that never arrived. The trying is real, and so is the exhaustion that comes with it. What tends to help is not more effort, but a different relationship with the alarm itself.</p>
          <p>So we get curious instead of forceful. What is the worry protecting? When does it fire, and what does it cost you to keep obeying it? Those questions sound simple, and they are not, but they are where the work usually begins.</p>
          <h3>How the work actually goes</h3>
          <p>It is solution-focused and practical, and it moves at your pace. We pay attention to the thoughts and to the body, because anxiety lives in both, and we start by making sure you feel genuinely understood. Not managed, not processed, understood. That is the part people say they were missing.</p>
          <p>Change comes the way it usually does, quietly and then all at once. The racing thoughts settle, the chest loosens, and an ordinary day starts to feel lighter than it has in a while.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

